DATA CLEANING

I removed car_ID variable from the dataset.

car_data <- car_data[,!names(car_data) %in% c("car_ID")]

Distinct car names are stored in car_names.

car_names <- c("alfa-romero", "audi", "bmw", "buick", "chevrolet", "dodge", "honda", "isuzu", 
               "jaguar", "mazda", "mercury", "mitsubishi", "nissan", "peugeot", "plymouth", 
               "plymouth", "porsche", "renault", "saab", "subaru", "toyota", "volkswagen", "volvo")

Rows of CarName variable are changed with distinct car names in the car_names.

for (i in car_names) {
  index <- which(str_detect(str_to_lower(car_data$CarName), fixed(i))==TRUE)
  car_data$CarName[index] <- i
}

There are some wrong typed car names like “maxda” instead of “mazda” and “toyouta” instead of “toyota”. Also some abbreviations are used like “vw” instead “volkswagen”. I corrected all of them.

I changed class of “character” variables to “factor”.

c_n <- colnames(car_data)

for (i in c_n) {
  if (class(car_data[[i]])=="character") {
    car_data[[i]] <- as.factor(car_data[[i]])
  }
}

car_data$symboling <- as.factor(car_data$symboling)

MISSING DATA IMPUTATION

I imputed missing values using mice packages’ “Classification and Regression Trees (CART)” method.

imputed_Data <- mice(car_data, m=1, maxit = 1, method = 'cart', seed = 500)
## 
##  iter imp variable
##   1   1  symboling  CarName  fueltype  aspiration  doornumber  carbody  drivewheel  enginelocation  wheelbase  carlength  carwidth  carheight  curbweight  enginetype  cylindernumber  enginesize  fuelsystem  boreratio  stroke  compressionratio  horsepower  peakrpm  citympg  highwaympg  price
complete_data<-mice::complete(imputed_Data,1)

FEATURE ENGINEERING

Symbolling variable in the data set represents the insurance risk of a car. While 3 indicates that the car has high level of insurance risk, 0 and lower integers represent the opposite. Based on symboling, new variable called “risky” was created. It has two levels “yes” and “no” showing the car has risky insurance or not.

complete_data$symboling <- as.numeric(complete_data$symboling) - 3

complete_data$risky <- ifelse(complete_data$symboling > 0, "yes", "no")

complete_data$risky <- as.factor(complete_data$risky)

complete_data <- complete_data %>% select(-symboling)

Numerical variables are in numerical_car_data to use in further steps.

numerical_car_col_names <- list()

for (i in colnames(complete_data)) {
  if (class(complete_data[[i]]) != "factor") {
    numerical_car_col_names[i] <- i
  }

APPLICATION OF DIFFERENT CROSS-VALIDATION TECHNIQUES

Four different Cross-Validation Methods namely, The Validation Set Approach, LOOCV, K-Fold Cross Validation and Repeated K-Fold Cross Validation, were applied to the dataset and compared based on certain performance measures known as RMSE, Rsquared and MAE.

1. The Validation set Approach

Splitting the data into training and test set.

set.seed(2)
training.samples <- complete_data$price %>% createDataPartition(p = 0.8, list = FALSE) #createDataPartition helps you define train set index 
train.data  <- complete_data[training.samples, ]
test.data <- complete_data[-training.samples, ]

Building the model.

set.seed(546)
model_lm <- lm(price ~., data = train.data)

Making prediction

predictions <- model_lm %>% predict(test.data)

info_linear <- data.frame( RMSE = RMSE(predictions, test.data$price), 
                           R2 = cor(predictions, test.data$price)^2, 
                           MAE = MAE(predictions, test.data$price))

colnames(info_linear) <- c("RMSE", "Rsquared", "MAE")

tr <- list()

  if(count[i] == max(count)) {
    tr[i] <- "darkred"
  }
  if(count[i] == min(count)) {
    tr[i] <- "darkblue"
  }
  if(count[i] != max(count) & count[i] != min(count)) {
    tr[i] <- "darkgrey"
  }

FUTURE SELECTION

Firstly, I will apply Ridge Regression. The aim is basically to find an optimal λ value which provides bias - variance balance. In this way, we can find the lowest potential MSE. Below “x” contains numerical variables without response (price).

x=model.matrix (price ∼ .,train.data)[,-1]

“y” includes price.

y=train.data$price

Ridge Regression

I will insert different values to λ ranging from 10^10 to 10^-2. Hence, we will have 100 different Ridge Regression coefficients.

grid =10^ seq (10,-2, length =100)
ridge.mod =glmnet (x,y,alpha =0, lambda =grid)

Elastic Regression

Below, we can see 21 different lambda, mse and alpha values obtained after applying cross-validation for every 21 different lambda values.

lambda <- c()
mse<-c()
alpha<-c()
for (i in 0:20) {
  alpha[i+1] <- paste0("alpha", i/20)
  set.seed(123)
  opt_lambda_val <-cv.glmnet(x,y, alpha=i/20)$lambda.min
  lambda[i+1]<-opt_lambda_val
  fit<-glmnet(x, y, alpha = i/20, lambda = opt_lambda_val)
  predicted<-predict(fit, s = opt_lambda_val, newx = x)
  mse[i+1]<-mean((y - predicted)^2)
}
comp_table<-data.frame(lambda,mse,alpha)

It is clear that most of the coefficients are similar in magnitude and sign. for OLS and three Robust Regression models. Cofficient of “buick” variable in OLS is negative and smaller in magnitude from the ones in Robust Regression. The same relation can be observed in the stroke variable except than sign is negative in OLS while they are posivite in Robust Regression models. Also, there is some differences between compressionratio variable’s coefficients of OLS and the others.

Performance measures of four type of models: The values are very close to each other. However, while MAE value is the lowest for bisquare, MSE and RMSE values are at their lowest in OLS model.

Positive association between “enginesize” and “new_response” is clear. However, the effect of enginesize changes by the value of carwidth. The effect of enginesize becomes higher as the level of carwidth increases. This is an indication of interaction.

ggplot(lm_data,aes(x=enginesize,y=new_response,colour=carwidth)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_gradient(low="darkorange",high = "steelblue") + theme_ipsum()

Before visual inspection of the interaction, we should apply centering. The aim of centering is that higher-order interactions may make lower-order effects unimportant. To see the real effects, we need centering.

price_y <- lm_data$new_response
carwidth_x1 <- lm_data$enginesize
curbweight_x2 <- lm_data$carwidth

carwidth_centered <- carwidth_x1 - mean(carwidth_x1) #centering
curbweight_centered <- curbweight_x2 - mean(curbweight_x2) #centering

data_centered <- data.frame(price_y, carwidth_centered, curbweight_centered)

vvg <- data.frame(price_y, carwidth_x1, curbweight_x2, carwidth_centered, curbweight_centered)


#Below model is the model with centered covariates.


ffit3<-lm(price_y ~ curbweight_centered + carwidth_centered + curbweight_centered:carwidth_centered,data = vvg)

According to Johnson-Neyman interval output, boundaries of the zone of significance are 89.57 and 156.78. These boundary values are actually centered values of horsepower variable, and within these boundaries, the relationship between price and enginesize is significant. Three simple slopes analysis shows that when horsepower traits are low, at their mean value or high, there is a significant positive relationship between enginesize and price. Hence, it is clear that the relationship between enginesize and price is not affected by the lower or higher levels of horsepower. Hence, it can be concluded that there is no interaction between enginesize and horsepower.

interactions::sim_slopes(

  confint = FALSE,

NEURAL NETWORK

Basically, Artificial Neural Networks were created by imitating the working system of the animal brain. Like in our brain, artificial networks consists of input that is the information entered to the system, nodes representing the brain cells linked each other via layers, and the output. Weights between the nodes works for determining how strongly each nodes affect each other and have a voice in determining the output. Below graph illustrates the basic construction of the Neural Networks.

For our car price dataset, NN gives the worst prediction measures (values are in the table which is at the bottom of the project), which are the highest error values for both train and test sets.

create scaling function.

scaler <- function(x){
  (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
}

Data preparation.

num_names <- c("wheelbase", "carlength", "carwidth", "carheight", "curbweight", "enginesize", 
               "boreratio", "stroke", "compressionratio", "horsepower", "peakrpm", "citympg", "highwaympg")

factorial_names <- colnames(train.data)[!(colnames(train.data) %in% num_names)]

scaled_numeric_train <- train.data[, num_names] %>% scaler()

train_nnet <- cbind(train.data[, factorial_names], scaled_numeric_train)
scaled_numeric_test <- test.data[, num_names] %>% scaler()

test_nnet <- cbind(test.data[, factorial_names], scaled_numeric_test)

Defining cross validation and the grid.

set.seed(9)
tr_control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=5, search="random")

grid <- expand.grid(size=c(seq(from=1, to=50, by=10)), 
                    decay=c(seq(from=0.0, to=0.3, by=0.1)))

Train the model.

plot(nn_model, rep = 'best')

plot.nnet(nn_model$finalModel)

MAE, MSE, RMSE and MAPE values are stored.

nn_predict_resp <- predict(nn_model, train_nnet)
nn_tr_1 <- MAE(as.numeric(nn_predict_resp),train_nnet$price)
nn_tr_2 <- MSE(as.numeric(nn_predict_resp),train_nnet$price)
nn_tr_3 <- RMSE(as.numeric(nn_predict_resp),train_nnet$price)
nn_tr_4 <- MAPE(as.numeric(nn_predict_resp),train_nnet$price)

nn_predict<-predict(nn_model,test_nnet)
nn_ts_1 <- MAE(as.numeric(nn_predict),test_nnet$price)
nn_ts_2 <- MSE(as.numeric(nn_predict),test_nnet$price)
nn_ts_3 <- RMSE(as.numeric(nn_predict),test_nnet$price)
nn_ts_4 <- MAPE(as.numeric(nn_predict),test_nnet$price)

SUPPORT VECTOR MACHINE

The primary usage of Support Vector Machine algorithm is to find an optimal lines called “Hyperplane” to distinctly classify the data points from each other. As it is seen from below graph, some points are determined as “support vectors” closer to the hyperplane. These points help to determine the margin of the classifier. Bold line represents the hyperplanes.

Defining cross validation and the grid.

set.seed(10)
tr_control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=5, search="random")

grid = expand.grid(C = seq(0, 2.5, length =12))
set.seed(11)
svmlinearFit <- train(price~., data=train_nnet,
                      trControl=tr_control, 
                      method = "svmLinear", savePredictions = T, 
                      tuneGrid=grid)
plot(svmlinearFit)

Decision Tree-Random Forest-XGBoost Regression

Decision Tree algorithms are used to classify points by comparing features step-by-step with each other. Starting from the root node, algorithm compares every attribute with each other until reaching the leaf node.

Decision Tree

Basic Tree structure of the DT model for our dataset can be seen below. It states that the average car price in the overall dataset is $14.000. Average price of the cars having enginesize greater than 182 is $33.000 and they constitutes only 10% of the whole dataset. Other 90% of the cars have engine size less than 182 and average price for them is $11.000. Cars having enginesize less than 182 and curbweight less than 2571 constitutes 58% of the whole dataset and they have average price of 8.530. The interpretation continues so on.

XGBoost

Xgboost is a much better method than the regular boosting method in that it computes second order gradient, also known as second order partial derivatives of the loss function This situation leads to more accurate calculations regarding the direction of the gradient. XGBOOST also includes certain regularization methods such as Ridge and Lasso Regression, which provide higher model generalization.

Xgboost gives the 2nd lowest MSE value for our dataset. Again, as it was for the GBM method, most of the points overlaps in the below trait fit graph. But, it is clear that model is good in catching splashes in the test data points.

In this study, primary goal was predicting car prices using different machine learning algorithms. Before prediction, one of the statistical techniques, Regression was applied and interaction between covariates was checked. After applying forward selection, discarding variables leading to multicollinearity and discarding the ones that are insignificant, it is seen that there is not much difference between the fitted lines of OLS model and Robust Regression Models. In the last part, performance measures of various machine learning algorithms was compared and it was detected that Random Forest model yielded moderate train set errors and the lowest test set errors. Hence, it is determined that the RF model is most suitable one for this dataset to make car price prediction.
